    INSERT INTO "Product" (id, code, title, description, price, "estimatedDays", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_1_id, 1, 'Introduction to Patents in India', 'Patents are exclusive rights granted by the government for inventions that are new, involve an inventive step, and are capable of industrial application. In India, patents are governed by the Patents Act 1970, which has been amended multiple times to align with TRIPS Agreement obligations. The Indian Patent Office (IPO), under the Controller General of Patents, Designs & Trade Marks, operates from four locations: Delhi, Mumbai, Chennai, and Kolkata. Understanding which office has jurisdiction based on your residence or place of business is crucial. India follows first-to-file system, meaning the first person to file gets priority regardless of who invented first. The patent term is 20 years from the filing date. India has emerged as a significant IP jurisdiction with over 66,000 patent applications filed annually and a growing emphasis on innovation through initiatives like Startup India, National IPR Policy 2016, and the establishment of CIPAM (Cell for IPR Promotion and Management). For startups, the IPR facilitation centers across India provide free IP awareness and filing assistance. The Indian IP ecosystem now includes Patent Information Centers in all states, Technology and Innovation Support Centers (TISCs), and specialized IP finance options through banks like SBI.', '["Research the four IPO locations and identify your jurisdictional office", "Review the Patents Act 1970 and 2005 amendments", "Identify IPR facilitation centers in your state", "Create a patent filing decision framework for your startup"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Patent Basics Checklist", "IPO Jurisdiction Finder", "Patent Term Calculator", "IP Decision Framework"], "tools": ["IP India Official Portal", "WIPO India Page", "CIPAM Resources", "State IPR Cell Directory"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_1_id, 2, 'Indian Patents Act 1970 Deep Dive', 'The Patents Act 1970, with its 2002, 2005, and subsequent amendments, forms the legal backbone of patent protection in India. Key provisions include Section 3 (what is not patentable - including mathematical methods, business methods, computer programs per se, and traditional knowledge), Section 2(1)(j) defining invention, Section 2(1)(ja) defining inventive step, Section 2(1)(ac) defining capable of industrial application, and importantly Section 3(d) which prevents evergreening of pharmaceutical patents - a uniquely Indian provision. Understanding the patent prosecution timeline is critical: examination request must be filed within 48 months of priority date, First Examination Report (FER) is typically issued within 1-3 months of examination request for expedited cases (6-12 months regular), response to FER must be filed within 6 months, and the entire prosecution from filing to grant typically takes 18-24 months for regular applications and 5-7 months under expedited examination for startups. The Act also contains provisions for compulsory licensing under Sections 84-92 (if patent is not worked in India within 3 years of grant, or if reasonable requirements are not met), government use under Section 100, and working statement requirements under Section 146. Recent amendments through the Patents Rules 2003 (as amended in 2020, 2021) have introduced online filing, expedited examination for startups, and reduced fees.', '["Study Section 3 exclusions and assess your invention against them", "Map your invention to patentability requirements under Sections 2(1)(j), 2(1)(ja), 2(1)(ac)", "Create timeline chart from filing to grant", "Research compulsory licensing provisions and their implications"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Section 3 Exclusion Analyzer", "Patentability Assessment Template", "Patent Timeline Planner", "Compulsory Licensing Risk Assessment"], "tools": ["Patents Act 1970 Full Text", "Patent Rules 2003 Updated", "IPAB Decisions Database", "Manual of Patent Practice"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_1_id, 3, 'Patentability Criteria in Indian Context', 'The three pillars of patentability in India are novelty (Section 2(1)(l)), inventive step (Section 2(1)(ja)), and capable of industrial application (Section 2(1)(ac)). Novelty means the invention is not anticipated by prior publication or prior use anywhere in the world before the priority date. In India, there is a 12-month grace period only for display at government-recognized exhibitions or publication in learned society journals - this is narrower than some other jurisdictions. Inventive step in India requires that the invention is not obvious to a person skilled in the art, having regard to prior art. The Indian standard for obviousness has been interpreted to require a technical advance or economic significance. Industrial applicability requires that the invention can be made or used in any industry. Indian examiners apply these criteria rigorously, particularly for software, business methods, and pharmaceutical inventions. For software patents, the key is to draft claims focusing on technical effect and hardware integration rather than the algorithm per se. For pharma, overcoming Section 3(d) requires demonstrating enhanced efficacy, not just new forms or derivatives. Recent Controller decisions and court judgments from Delhi and Bombay High Courts have provided guidance on interpreting these criteria, particularly the IPAB decision in Ferid Allani case for computer-related inventions and the Novartis Supreme Court judgment for Section 3(d).', '["Assess your invention against each patentability criterion", "Research prior art in Indian patent database (InPASS)", "Analyze recent Controller decisions in your technology area", "Document technical advance and economic significance"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Novelty Assessment Form", "Inventive Step Analysis Template", "Industrial Applicability Checklist", "Prior Art Documentation Matrix"], "tools": ["InPASS Patent Search", "IPO e-Register", "IPAB Decisions Archive", "Delhi High Court IP Judgments"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_1_id, 4, 'Types of IP Protection in India', 'India offers multiple IP protection mechanisms: patents (20 years from filing), design registrations (15 years from filing), trademarks (10 years, renewable indefinitely), copyrights (60 years after creator death), geographical indications (10 years, renewable), plant varieties (6-18 years depending on type), and trade secrets (no registration, perpetual protection through contract and confidence). For startups, choosing the right protection depends on the nature of innovation. Technical inventions with industrial application warrant patents. Aesthetic designs and product shapes qualify for design registration (much faster, typically 6-12 months). Brand names, logos, and slogans need trademark protection. Software can be protected through copyright (automatic) and potentially patents if technical effect is demonstrated. Manufacturing processes and formulas can be protected as trade secrets if proper confidentiality measures are implemented. The Indian IP framework allows layered protection - for example, a product can have patent protection for its mechanism, design registration for its appearance, and trademark protection for its brand. Understanding protection duration and maintenance costs is crucial: patent annual fees start at Rs 4,800 (year 3-6) and increase to Rs 80,000 (year 20) for large entities; startups pay 80% less. Design renewal costs Rs 4,000 every 5 years. Trademark renewal costs Rs 9,000 every 10 years. Strategic IP portfolio planning should consider protection scope, duration, cost, and enforceability.', '["Map your innovations to appropriate IP protection types", "Calculate total IP protection costs over 20 years", "Identify layered protection opportunities", "Create IP protection priority matrix"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["IP Type Selection Matrix", "IP Cost Calculator (20-Year)", "Layered Protection Planner", "IP Portfolio Strategy Template"], "tools": ["IPO Fee Calculator", "Design Registration Portal", "Trademark Registry", "Copyright Office Portal"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_1_id, 5, 'Patent vs Trade Secret Decision Framework', 'The choice between patent and trade secret protection is strategic and irreversible. Patents provide exclusive rights for 20 years but require public disclosure of the invention. Trade secrets offer potentially indefinite protection but can be lost through independent discovery, reverse engineering, or breach of confidence. In India, trade secrets are protected through contract law, equity principles, and the Information Technology Act 2000 for digital information. Key factors for decision: Can the invention be reverse-engineered? If yes, patent is preferable. Is the innovation likely to be independently discovered? Patents provide stronger protection. What is the technology lifecycle? Short lifecycle may favor trade secrets to avoid disclosure. What are enforcement capabilities? Trade secrets require strict internal controls; patents require litigation readiness. For startups, the 80% fee discount makes patenting more affordable. However, trade secrets may be appropriate for manufacturing processes, algorithms that are not visible in products, customer databases, and internal methodologies. Indian courts have upheld trade secret protection in several cases including John Richard Brady v. Chemical Process Equipments, Burlington Home Shopping v. Rajnish Chibber, and more recent cases involving employee non-compete and confidentiality. Implementing trade secret protection requires confidentiality agreements with employees, vendors, and partners; marking documents confidential; access controls; exit interviews; and regular audits. Document all trade secret protection measures as evidence for potential litigation.', '["Evaluate patent vs trade secret for each innovation", "Assess reverse engineering vulnerability", "Draft confidentiality agreement templates", "Create trade secret protection protocol"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Patent vs Trade Secret Decision Matrix", "Reverse Engineering Risk Assessment", "Confidentiality Agreement Template (India)", "Trade Secret Protection Checklist"], "tools": ["Trade Secret Audit Tool", "NDA Generator", "Employee Exit Protocol", "Information Classification System"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_2_id, 6, 'Indian Patent Database Search (InPASS)', 'The Indian Patent Advanced Search System (InPASS) is the official database for searching Indian patents and patent applications. It contains over 3.5 lakh published applications and granted patents. Search strategies include keyword search (using title, abstract, claims, and description), IPC classification search (using the hierarchical International Patent Classification system), applicant/inventor search, and date-based search. For effective searching: use Boolean operators (AND, OR, NOT), wildcards (* for multiple characters, ? for single character), and phrase search using quotes. The InPASS database is updated weekly with new publications. Understanding document types is crucial: complete specifications after 18 months publication (published applications), granted patents, and working statements (Form 27). The e-Register provides real-time status of any application including examination status, objections raised, and grant details. For comprehensive Indian prior art search, also search: published research papers from Indian journals, thesis databases from universities, published standards from BIS, and technical publications from CSIR laboratories. Indian Patent Office also publishes the Official Journal weekly containing all newly published applications - useful for monitoring competitor filings. Set up alerts on InPASS for specific technology areas, applicants, or IPC classes to track new filings relevant to your domain.', '["Register for InPASS account and complete tutorial", "Conduct sample searches using different parameters", "Identify relevant IPC classifications for your technology", "Set up monitoring alerts for competitors"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["InPASS Search Strategy Template", "IPC Classification Finder", "Prior Art Documentation Form", "Competitor Monitoring Setup Guide"], "tools": ["InPASS Portal", "IPO e-Register", "IPO Official Journal", "IPC Classification Database"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_2_id, 7, 'International Patent Database Search', 'Comprehensive prior art search requires searching international databases as India follows absolute novelty standard. Key databases: USPTO (PatFT for granted, AppFT for applications) contains 11+ million US patents; Espacenet (EPO) provides access to 140+ million documents from 100+ countries; WIPO PATENTSCOPE contains 100+ million documents including all PCT applications; Google Patents offers full-text search across major jurisdictions; Lens.org provides free comprehensive search with citation analysis. Each database has strengths: USPTO has excellent full-text search and examiner cited references; Espacenet has the best coverage and machine translation; PATENTSCOPE has powerful sequence and chemical search; Google Patents offers natural language search. Search strategy should combine: conceptual search (what does the invention do), structural search (how is it made), and classification search (IPC, CPC, USPC). For thorough search, use at least three different databases with different search strategies. Document all searches with date, database, query, and results for patent prosecution defense. Prior art includes not just patents but also: scientific publications (search PubMed, Google Scholar, IEEE Xplore), conference proceedings, standards documents, product brochures and websites (use Wayback Machine for dated evidence), and thesis databases. The search date is critical - prior art must predate your priority date. For PCT applications, international search report provides good prior art overview from the International Searching Authority.', '["Complete searches in USPTO, Espacenet, and PATENTSCOPE", "Document all search queries and results systematically", "Identify most relevant prior art documents", "Analyze citation patterns in found patents"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Multi-Database Search Protocol", "Prior Art Results Matrix", "Citation Analysis Template", "Search Documentation Log"], "tools": ["USPTO Patent Search", "Espacenet", "WIPO PATENTSCOPE", "Google Patents", "Lens.org"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_2_id, 8, 'Patentability Assessment from Search Results', 'Converting prior art search results into patentability assessment requires systematic analysis. First, categorize found documents by relevance: X (highly relevant, anticipates claim), Y (relevant when combined with other documents), A (background, defines general state of art), and E (earlier application with later publication, relevant for novelty only). For each X and Y document, conduct element-by-element comparison with your invention. Create a claim chart mapping each element of your anticipated claims to teachings in prior art. Identify gaps - elements not found in prior art are your potential novelty and inventive step. Novelty analysis: does any single document disclose all elements of your claim? If yes, the claim lacks novelty and must be narrowed. Inventive step analysis: would a person skilled in the art, knowing the prior art, find your invention obvious? Consider whether combining two or more references would be obvious - what motivation would exist to combine? Indian examiners apply the "could-would" test: could a skilled person arrive at the invention, and would they have done so without hindsight? Economic significance and technical effect support inventive step. Based on analysis, refine your invention disclosure to emphasize novel features, narrow scope if needed, and identify strongest aspects for claims. This analysis also reveals freedom-to-operate issues - existing patents that your product might infringe. Document the assessment thoroughly as it supports prosecution arguments and due diligence.', '["Categorize all found prior art using X/Y/A/E system", "Create element-by-element comparison charts", "Identify novelty and inventive step arguments", "Document freedom-to-operate concerns"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Prior Art Categorization Matrix", "Claim Chart Template", "Inventive Step Analysis Form", "FTO Preliminary Assessment"], "tools": ["Claim Charting Tool", "Element Comparison Spreadsheet", "Patentability Score Calculator", "FTO Risk Tracker"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_2_id, 9, 'Freedom to Operate (FTO) Analysis', 'Freedom to Operate analysis determines whether your product or process can be commercialized without infringing existing patent rights. In India, patent infringement requires making, using, selling, offering for sale, or importing a patented invention without license. FTO analysis should cover: currently granted patents (enforceable immediately), pending applications (potential future risk), and international patents that may enter India national phase. For each relevant patent, analyze: (1) Are all claim elements present in your product? If any element is missing, no infringement. (2) Is the patent still in force? Check annual fee payment status on e-Register. (3) What is the territorial scope? Indian patents only cover India. (4) Are there defense strategies? Section 107A provides exceptions for research, experiments, and Bolar provision for regulatory approval. Risk assessment should categorize patents as: high risk (all elements matched, patent valid, strong claims), medium risk (most elements matched, some differences arguable), low risk (significant differences, weak claims, or validity concerns). For high-risk patents, options include: design around (modify product to avoid infringement), license negotiation, validity challenge (pre-grant opposition under Section 25(1), post-grant opposition under Section 25(2), or revocation petition under Section 64), or acquire the patent. FTO should be documented formally and updated regularly as patent landscape changes. For investor due diligence, FTO opinions from patent attorneys are often required.', '["Identify all potentially relevant granted patents", "Conduct claim-by-claim infringement analysis", "Assess patent validity and enforceability", "Create risk mitigation strategy for high-risk patents"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["FTO Analysis Template", "Claim Mapping Matrix", "Risk Categorization Framework", "Design-Around Checklist"], "tools": ["Patent Status Checker", "Claim Element Analyzer", "FTO Risk Dashboard", "License Negotiation Planner"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_2_id, 10, 'Competitive Patent Landscape Analysis', 'Competitive landscape analysis maps patent holdings across your technology domain to inform strategy. Start by identifying competitors: direct competitors, adjacent market players, research institutions, and technology giants with broad portfolios. For each competitor, analyze: total patent portfolio (India and global), filing trends over time, technology focus areas (using IPC analysis), geographic coverage, and citation patterns (who cites them, who they cite). Create visualization: patent landscape maps showing technology clusters, filing timeline charts, geographic heat maps, and inventor network diagrams. Key insights to extract: emerging technology trends (increasing filings indicate hot areas), white spaces (areas with few filings - opportunity or dead end?), dominant players and their focus, and acquisition targets (companies with valuable but undermonetized patents). For startups, landscape analysis helps: position innovation in uncrowded spaces, identify licensing opportunities, find potential partners or acquirers, and prepare for investor due diligence questions. Indian landscape specifics: many multinationals file in India as part of PCT national phase (check 31-month deadline), Indian pharmaceutical companies file heavily in NCE and formulation space, IT services companies file less than product companies, and research institutions like CSIR, IITs, and IISc have significant portfolios often available for licensing. Update landscape analysis quarterly as patent filing data has 18-month lag from filing to publication.', '["Create competitor list with patent portfolio sizes", "Analyze filing trends and technology focus", "Build patent landscape visualization", "Identify strategic opportunities from analysis"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Competitor Patent Matrix", "Filing Trend Analysis Template", "Technology Cluster Map Framework", "Strategic Opportunity Identifier"], "tools": ["Patent Analytics Platform", "Citation Network Visualizer", "IPC Trend Analyzer", "Landscape Mapping Tool"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_3_id, 11, 'Invention Disclosure Document Preparation', 'The invention disclosure document (IDD) is the foundation of your patent application. A comprehensive IDD captures all aspects of the invention before drafting begins. Essential elements include: title (descriptive but not limiting), technical field (broad but accurate), background (prior art problems without admitting specifics), invention summary (concise statement of what the invention does and how), detailed description (enough detail for skilled person to reproduce), examples/embodiments (specific implementations, preferably multiple), drawings (even rough sketches help drafters understand), advantages (technical and economic benefits), and inventor details (all contributors who conceived the invention). In Indian context, additional considerations: clearly distinguish from prior art to support inventive step, document technical effect for software inventions, provide data supporting enhanced efficacy for pharma inventions, and identify any traditional knowledge to avoid Section 3(p) issues. The IDD should answer: What problem does it solve? How does it work? What are the key novel features? What variations are possible? Who invented it and when? Tips for effective IDDs: write for someone unfamiliar with your specific project, include unsuccessful approaches (helps define scope), date all documents, and maintain confidentiality until filing. Many Indian startups use invention capture forms that prompt inventors through these sections. Regular invention harvesting sessions with R&D teams help identify patentable innovations early. The IDD quality directly impacts application quality and prosecution success.', '["Create invention disclosure template for your organization", "Document current invention comprehensively", "Identify all potential inventors accurately", "Establish invention capture process for ongoing innovations"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Invention Disclosure Form", "Technical Problem Statement Template", "Embodiment Documentation Guide", "Inventor Identification Checklist"], "tools": ["IDD Management System", "Drawing Sketch Tool", "Prior Art Integration Template", "Confidentiality Protocol"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_3_id, 12, 'Patent Claims Drafting', 'Claims define the legal scope of patent protection - they are the most critical part of the application. In India, claim interpretation follows purposive construction balanced with fair protection. Claim types: independent claims (stand alone, define complete invention), dependent claims (incorporate and narrow independent claims), method/process claims, apparatus/system claims, product claims, and use claims (limited acceptance in India). Drafting principles: start broad, then narrow through dependent claims; use the preamble-body format (preamble: context, body: novel elements); avoid unnecessary limitations that narrow scope; ensure claims read on embodiments in specification; and maintain consistent terminology. Indian-specific considerations: Section 10(4) requires claims to relate to single invention or inventive concept; Section 10(5) requires claims to be based on and fairly supported by description; omnibus claims (referring to specification or drawings) are not allowed. Claim strategies: draft multiple independent claims covering different aspects (method, system, product); use dependent claims to capture important variations; include fallback positions anticipating examiner objections. Typical application has 10-20 claims. Additional claims beyond 10 incur fees of Rs 800 each (startups: Rs 160). For software inventions, claim hardware integration or technical effect; for pharma, claim specific compounds with data rather than broad genera. Review competitor claim styles in your technology area to understand examiner expectations. Claims must be supported by specification - add embodiments before broadening claims.', '["Draft independent and dependent claims for your invention", "Ensure claims cover commercial embodiment", "Check claim support in specification", "Analyze competitor claim styles in your field"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Claim Drafting Template", "Claim Tree Diagram", "Claim Support Checklist", "Claim Strategy Matrix"], "tools": ["Claim Language Library", "Claim Breadth Analyzer", "Support Verification Tool", "Claim Fee Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_3_id, 13, 'Specification Writing for Indian Applications', 'The complete specification under Section 10 must sufficiently describe the invention to enable a person skilled in the art to perform it. Structure: title of invention (concise, indicative), technical field (one paragraph), background (prior art without admitting specifics, problem to be solved), summary of invention (matching claim scope), brief description of drawings, detailed description (best mode and multiple embodiments), examples (working examples preferred), claims, and abstract (150 words max). Writing standards: use present tense for general descriptions, past tense for experiments; maintain consistent terminology throughout; define technical terms when first used; number paragraphs for easy reference; cross-reference drawings appropriately. Indian-specific requirements: best mode disclosure is required under Section 10(4)(b); specification must show how method is performed or article constructed; must disclose source and geographical origin for biological material. For software inventions, describe technical architecture, algorithms as flow charts, hardware interaction, and technical effect achieved. For pharma, include synthesis routes, characterization data, and efficacy data for Section 3(d) compliance. Specification should be enabling without being limiting - describe what is required to practice the invention while keeping flexibility for claim scope. The specification cannot be expanded after filing (no new matter), so include all possible variations and embodiments upfront. Professional drafters typically create specifications of 20-50 pages depending on complexity.', '["Draft complete specification following Section 10 requirements", "Include multiple embodiments for claim flexibility", "Cross-check specification supports all claims", "Review for enabling disclosure"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Complete Specification Template (India)", "Embodiment Description Framework", "Example Documentation Format", "Specification Review Checklist"], "tools": ["Specification Structure Validator", "Term Consistency Checker", "Drawing Reference Manager", "Best Mode Verification Tool"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_3_id, 14, 'Patent Drawings and Figures', 'Patent drawings are essential for understanding the invention and are often the first thing examiners review. Indian Patent Rules prescribe drawing requirements: A4 size, minimum margins (top 2.5cm, left 2.5cm, right 1.5cm, bottom 1cm), black ink on white paper, reference numerals must correspond to specification, scale appropriate for reduction, no coloring or shading (only hatching for cross-sections). Drawing types include: perspective views (show 3D structure), exploded views (show assembly), cross-sectional views (show internal structure), flow charts (for methods and processes), block diagrams (for systems), circuit diagrams, and screenshots (for software UI). Best practices: use consistent reference numerals throughout drawings and specification; include multiple views to fully disclose invention; label significant features; show alternative embodiments; for method claims, include flow charts with decision points. For software inventions, drawings are crucial: system architecture diagrams, data flow diagrams, sequence diagrams, user interface screenshots (showing technical features), and algorithm flowcharts help demonstrate technical effect and patentability. Professional patent drawings typically cost Rs 1,000-3,000 per sheet in India. For provisional applications, informal drawings are acceptable, but complete applications require formal drawings meeting specifications. Drawing sheets are counted for fees (first 30 pages free for startups, Rs 160 per additional 10 pages). Number drawings as Figure 1, Figure 2, etc., and reference in specification as "as shown in Figure 1."', '["Create formal drawings meeting IPO specifications", "Ensure reference numerals match specification", "Include all views necessary to understand invention", "Add flow charts for method claims"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Drawing Specification Template (A4)", "Reference Numeral Management Sheet", "View Selection Guide", "Flowchart Symbol Library"], "tools": ["Patent Drawing Software", "Margin Verification Tool", "Reference Number Generator", "Figure Numbering System"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_3_id, 15, 'Software and Computer-Related Invention Drafting', 'Patenting software in India requires careful drafting to overcome Section 3(k) which excludes "computer program per se." The key is demonstrating technical effect beyond the inherent effect of running a program. The 2016 Guidelines for Examination of Computer Related Inventions (CRI Guidelines) and 2017 revised guidelines provide framework. Patentable: inventions with technical contribution - improved computer performance, better resource utilization, improved security, new industrial process control, technical solution to technical problem. Not patentable: mere business methods implemented on computer, algorithms without technical application, methods of mental acts automated on computer. Drafting strategies: (1) Claim as computer-implemented method with technical effect clearly stated, (2) Include hardware elements in independent claims (processor, memory, storage), (3) Describe technical problem and technical solution, (4) Include system claims with physical components, (5) Avoid purely business method language. Specification should detail: technical architecture, hardware-software interaction, data processing showing technical effect, performance improvements with data if available. The Ferid Allani IPAB decision (2013) established that computer programs with technical effect are patentable. Recent Controller decisions have granted patents for machine learning systems, cybersecurity methods, and industrial IoT applications where technical effect is clear. Include comparison with prior art systems showing technical advance. For AI/ML inventions, focus on the technical problem solved, not the algorithm itself. Claims like "A method for [technical process] comprising: receiving by a processor... processing by the processor... transmitting..." have better acceptance than pure method claims.', '["Identify and articulate technical effect of software invention", "Draft claims with hardware elements", "Prepare technical comparison with prior art", "Document performance improvements with data"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["CRI Drafting Template", "Technical Effect Statement Generator", "Hardware-Software Integration Claims", "Prior Art Technical Comparison Matrix"], "tools": ["CRI Guidelines Reference", "Claim Language Generator for Software", "Technical Effect Validator", "Section 3(k) Compliance Checker"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_4_id, 16, 'IP India E-Filing System Setup', 'The IP India e-filing portal (ipindiaonline.gov.in) is mandatory for all patent filings since 2018. Account setup requires: digital signature certificate (DSC) from licensed certifying authority (cost Rs 1,500-3,000 for 2 years), user registration with email and mobile verification, and link DSC to account. Account types: individual applicant, registered patent agent, or organization. For startups, register as startup on DPIIT portal first to claim fee benefits. E-filing portal provides: application filing, fee payment (net banking, debit/credit card), document submission, correspondence receipt, status tracking. Key features: auto-generation of application number, electronic receipt, SMS/email notifications, online payment gateway. Technical requirements: Windows OS, Internet Explorer (or Edge with IE mode), Java enabled, DSC token driver installed. Common issues: DSC not recognized (update driver), payment failure (use net banking backup), document upload errors (PDF under 10MB, OCR-compatible). Practice using the portal with test filings before actual submission. The portal has jurisdiction selection - ensure you select correct IPO based on applicant address. Form selection depends on application type: Form 1 for application, Form 2 for specification, Form 3 for statement and undertaking, Form 5 for declaration of inventorship. Understanding the portal reduces filing errors and delays.', '["Obtain DSC from licensed certifying authority", "Register on IP India e-filing portal", "Complete DPIIT startup registration if applicable", "Practice portal navigation with test account"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["DSC Application Checklist", "Portal Registration Guide", "DPIIT Startup Registration Steps", "E-Filing Test Checklist"], "tools": ["IP India E-Filing Portal", "DSC Provider List", "DPIIT Startup Portal", "Browser Compatibility Checker"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_4_id, 17, 'Provisional vs Complete Application Strategy', 'Indian law allows two filing strategies: direct complete application, or provisional application followed by complete application within 12 months. Provisional application (Form 2 provisional): establishes priority date with lower fee, allows "Patent Pending" status, gives 12 months to develop invention further and assess commercial viability, requires only description (no claims), fee Rs 1,600 (startup: Rs 320). Complete application (Form 2 complete): full specification with claims required, can be filed directly or after provisional, examination only begins after complete filing, fee Rs 8,000 (startup: Rs 1,600). Strategic considerations: Use provisional when: invention is early stage, commercial potential unclear, need priority date quickly, expect improvements within 12 months, testing multiple approaches. Use direct complete when: invention fully developed, clear commercial application, prior art risk requires quick examination, international filing planned (PCT clock starts from complete). Important: provisional establishes priority only for matter disclosed - new matter in complete is not backdated. If provisional lapses without complete filing, application is abandoned and disclosure becomes prior art. For startups, provisional at Rs 320 is excellent for establishing early priority at minimal cost. Multiple provisionals can be consolidated in one complete application within 12 months of first provisional. Convention priority (from foreign filing) can also be claimed within 12 months.', '["Evaluate provisional vs complete filing for your invention", "Calculate cost comparison for both routes", "Create filing timeline based on strategy", "Prepare appropriate application forms"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Filing Strategy Decision Matrix", "Provisional Application Template", "Complete Application Template", "Timeline Planning Chart"], "tools": ["Fee Calculator (Startup vs Regular)", "Priority Date Tracker", "12-Month Deadline Calculator", "Form Selection Guide"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_4_id, 18, 'Startup India Patent Benefits', 'Startup India (DPIIT) registration provides significant patent benefits: 80% fee reduction on all patent fees including filing, examination, and maintenance; expedited examination (decision within 6 months vs 18-24 months regular); access to panel of facilitators for free patent filing assistance. Eligibility: entity registered as private limited, partnership, or LLP; under 10 years from incorporation; turnover under Rs 100 crore in any year; working towards innovation/improvement (not mere trading). Registration process: create account on Startup India portal, provide incorporation details, submit certificate of incorporation, describe innovative nature, receive DPIIT recognition certificate. Fee savings example: regular filing fee Rs 8,000 vs startup Rs 1,600; examination request Rs 4,000 vs Rs 800; first renewal (year 3) Rs 4,800 vs Rs 960. Total savings over patent life can exceed Rs 3 lakhs. Expedited examination under Rule 24C: file Form 18A with expedition request; examination report typically within 1 month; total grant within 5-7 months if no major objections; Rs 8,000 fee (startup: Rs 1,600). Facilitator scheme: apply through Startup India portal for free assistance from panel of patent agents; covers prior art search, drafting, filing, and prosecution; limited to first patent application. Small entity (not startup) also gets 50% discount but no expedited examination. Maintain startup status by not crossing eligibility thresholds. Annual verification may be required.', '["Complete DPIIT startup registration", "Calculate fee savings for your filing plans", "Identify expedited examination opportunity", "Apply for facilitator assistance if needed"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["DPIIT Application Checklist", "Fee Comparison Calculator (Startup vs Regular)", "Expedited Examination Request Template", "Facilitator Application Guide"], "tools": ["Startup India Portal", "DPIIT Recognition Tracker", "Form 18A Generator", "Facilitator Panel Directory"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_4_id, 19, 'Patent Filing Forms and Fees', 'Indian patent filing requires multiple forms with specific fees. Form 1 (Application for Patent): contains applicant details, title, priority claims, inventor declaration; fee Rs 1,600 (startup: Rs 320); must be signed by applicant or authorized agent. Form 2 (Specification): provisional or complete specification; fee Rs 1,600 provisional, Rs 8,000 complete (startup 80% off); includes claims in complete. Form 3 (Statement and Undertaking): declares corresponding foreign applications; mandatory for Indian residents filing abroad; penalty for non-compliance; must be updated within 6 months of any foreign filing. Form 5 (Declaration of Inventorship): required when applicant is not inventor; establishes how right to apply was acquired; fee Rs 400 (startup: Rs 80). Form 18 (Request for Examination): triggers examination process; must be filed within 48 months of priority date; fee Rs 4,000 (startup: Rs 800). Form 18A (Expedited Examination): for startups; fee Rs 8,000 (startup: Rs 1,600). Additional fees: each claim beyond 10: Rs 800 (startup: Rs 160); each page beyond 30: Rs 160 per 10 pages (startup: Rs 32); each priority claim: Rs 1,600 (startup: Rs 320). Payment through e-filing portal using net banking, credit/debit card. Keep payment receipts for records. Note: fees are indexed and may change - verify current fees on IP India website before filing.', '["Prepare all required forms for filing", "Calculate total filing fees based on claims and pages", "Gather supporting documents (POA, assignment)", "Set up payment method on e-filing portal"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Form 1 Template with Instructions", "Form 2 Checklist", "Form 3 Foreign Filing Tracker", "Fee Calculation Spreadsheet"], "tools": ["IP India Fee Schedule", "Form Auto-Fill Tool", "Payment Gateway Guide", "Receipt Management System"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_4_id, 20, 'Foreign Filing License and National Security', 'Section 39 requires foreign filing license (FFL) before filing outside India if invention made in India. This is a national security provision to prevent sensitive technology leaving India without review. Process: file Form 25 (application for FFL) with complete invention details; fee Rs 8,000 (startup: Rs 1,600); Controller reviews and grants/refuses within specified period (typically 21 days if no objection); silence after 21 days means deemed grant. What triggers FFL requirement: invention conceived in India by Indian resident; invention developed in India regardless of inventor residence. Exemptions: first filing made in India (can file abroad after 6 weeks without separate FFL per Section 39(1)); or direction from Central Government to file abroad. Consequences of non-compliance: patent granted in India can be revoked; up to 2 years imprisonment; inventor/agent disqualified. PCT route from India: filing PCT application with IP India as receiving office satisfies first filing requirement; international search happens parallel to FFL review. Strategic consideration: for sensitive technology, FFL review may take longer; plan international filing timeline accordingly. Industries with higher scrutiny: defense, nuclear, certain electronics, certain chemicals. For startups in non-sensitive sectors, FFL is typically routine. Document the location of invention development clearly in records. If invention made in India by non-resident, FFL still required if filing specification in India first.', '["Assess FFL requirement for your invention", "Prepare Form 25 if needed", "Plan international filing timeline around FFL", "Document invention location clearly"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["FFL Assessment Checklist", "Form 25 Template", "International Filing Timeline Planner", "Invention Location Documentation"], "tools": ["FFL Decision Tool", "Section 39 Guide", "21-Day Tracker", "PCT Timeline Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_5_id, 21, 'PCT System Fundamentals', 'The Patent Cooperation Treaty (PCT) enables filing a single international application designating 157 member countries. India has been PCT member since 1998. PCT provides: single filing covering multiple countries, 18-month delay before national phase (up to 30-31 months from priority), centralized search and preliminary examination, standardized format accepted worldwide. PCT does NOT grant international patent - it provides pathway to national/regional patents. Cost advantage: defer major costs (translations, national fees, local attorneys) until commercial potential validated. PCT timeline: file international application (within 12 months of priority for convention); international search report and written opinion within 3 months; optional supplementary international search; 18-month publication; optional Chapter II examination; 30-31 months deadline for national phase entry (varies by country). For Indian applicants: file with IP India as Receiving Office (RO/IN); Indian Patent Office can be International Searching Authority (ISA/IN) at lower cost than EPO or USPTO; ISA/IN search fee approximately Rs 10,000 for startups. Total PCT filing cost for Indian startup: approximately Rs 1.5-2 lakhs including search, much lower than individual national filings. PCT is essential for startups planning international markets or seeking global investors who expect international IP protection.', '["Understand PCT timeline and deadlines", "Identify target countries for national phase", "Calculate PCT cost vs direct national filing", "Determine ISA preference (IN, EP, US)"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["PCT Timeline Chart", "Country Selection Matrix", "PCT Cost Calculator", "ISA Comparison Guide"], "tools": ["WIPO PCT Guide", "ePCT Portal", "National Phase Deadline Calculator", "ISA Fee Comparison Tool"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_5_id, 22, 'Filing PCT Application from India', 'PCT international application from India is filed with Indian Patent Office as Receiving Office (RO/IN). Filing options: paper filing at IPO Delhi or e-filing through ePCT system (preferred). ePCT requirements: WIPO customer account, digital certificate (can use Indian DSC), web browser access. Forms: PCT Request Form (PCT/RO/101) generated online, specification, claims, drawings in WIPO format. Fees payable to RO/IN: transmittal fee (Rs 4,000), international filing fee (approximately Rs 1 lakh, reduced for developing country applicant), search fee (depends on ISA chosen). Fee reductions: 90% reduction in international filing fee for natural person applicants from developing countries (India qualifies); startup discount applicable to RO fees. Language: can file in English (no translation needed for ISA/IN, ISA/EP, ISA/US). Priority claim: from Indian provisional or complete application filed within preceding 12 months; priority document can be accessed through DAS (Digital Access Service) or submitted manually. Filing tips: use ePCT document upload feature for specification; ensure claims are in separate document for fee calculation; verify format compliance using WIPO XML validator; obtain filing receipt with international application number (format: PCT/IN/year/number). Common mistakes: missing inventor declaration, incorrect applicant designation, priority claim errors, fee payment issues. File well before deadline to address any defects.', '["Set up ePCT account and link to WIPO customer number", "Prepare documents in WIPO-compliant format", "Calculate and pay appropriate fees", "Verify priority claim from Indian application"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["PCT Request Form Guide", "ePCT Filing Checklist", "WIPO Format Specification Template", "Priority Claim Documentation"], "tools": ["ePCT Online Filing", "WIPO Fee Calculator", "DAS Access Portal", "Document Format Validator"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_5_id, 23, 'International Search and Written Opinion', 'After PCT filing, International Searching Authority (ISA) conducts prior art search and issues International Search Report (ISR) and Written Opinion (WO/ISA). ISA options for Indian applicants: ISA/IN (Indian Patent Office - lowest cost, good for general technologies), ISA/EP (European Patent Office - higher cost, excellent for electronics/software/pharmaceuticals), ISA/US (USPTO - good for US-focused applications). ISR contains: prior art citations categorized as X, Y, A, etc.; statement of applicability of prior art to claims. Written Opinion provides: preliminary patentability analysis (novelty, inventive step, industrial applicability); clarity objections; unity of invention assessment. Timeline: ISR and WO issued within 3 months of search copy transmission or 9 months from priority date, whichever is later. Responding to WO: amendments and arguments can be filed under Article 19 (claims only) or Article 34 (Chapter II, broader changes). Strategy: analyze WO to predict national phase objections; prepare amendments/arguments before national phase; use WO feedback to refine claims. Publication: international application published at 18 months with ISR (if available). For Indian applicants, ISA/IN provides competent searching at approximately Rs 10,000 (startup rate) compared to Rs 1.5+ lakhs for ISA/EP. However, for key markets, ISA/EP search may carry more weight with national examiners.', '["Select appropriate ISA based on technology and target markets", "Analyze ISR and Written Opinion thoroughly", "Prepare Article 19 amendments if beneficial", "Document response strategy for national phase"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["ISA Selection Decision Matrix", "ISR Analysis Template", "Written Opinion Response Framework", "Article 19 Amendment Checklist"], "tools": ["ISA Fee Comparison Calculator", "Prior Art Citation Analyzer", "WO Response Generator", "Patent Family Tracker"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_5_id, 24, 'India National Phase Entry', 'PCT applications designating India must enter national phase within 31 months from priority date. Entry requirements: Form 1 (national phase application); Form 2 (specification in English, or translation if filed in other language); verified translation if not in English; Form 3 (statement of corresponding applications); priority document (if not accessed through DAS); power of attorney (if filing through agent); fee payment. National phase fees for startups: Rs 1,600 (filing) + Rs 800 (examination request if filed simultaneously). Additional requirements: Form 5 (declaration of inventorship) within 1 month of entry; Form 3 update within 6 months of national phase. Amendments: claims can be amended at entry to address ISR/WO objections; specification changes limited to matter in international publication. Examination: request for examination required within 48 months from priority (not from national phase entry); expedited examination available for startups. Timeline tip: enter national phase early if seeking expedited examination, as 48-month examination request deadline runs from original priority date. Common issues: deadline miscalculation (count exactly 31 months from earliest priority), missing documents (priority document, translations), form errors (inconsistent applicant names across documents). WIPO ePCT provides national phase entry deadlines and document checklist for India.', '["Calculate exact 31-month national phase deadline", "Prepare all required documents for entry", "Consider claim amendments based on ISR/WO", "File examination request timing strategy"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["India National Phase Checklist", "Document Preparation Guide", "Amendment at Entry Template", "Examination Timing Calculator"], "tools": ["31-Month Deadline Calculator", "National Phase Fee Calculator", "Translation Requirement Checker", "DAS Priority Document Tool"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_5_id, 25, 'National Phase Strategy for Key Jurisdictions', 'Strategic national phase entry requires balancing cost, market importance, and filing requirements. Key jurisdictions for Indian startups: USA (largest market for many technologies, 30-month deadline, USPTO has high standards), Europe (EPO for 39 countries, 31-month deadline, consider validation costs), China (second largest economy, CNIPA requires Chinese translation, 30-month deadline), Japan (important for electronics/automotive, JPO, 30-month deadline), India (home market, IPO, 31-month deadline). Cost considerations: USA national phase approximately $2,000-5,000; EPO approximately $3,000-6,000 plus validation costs; China approximately $1,500-3,000 including translation; Japan approximately $3,000-5,000. Regional systems: EPO allows single application for 39 countries, but requires validation in each country after grant; ARIPO and OAPI for African countries; Eurasian Patent Organization for CIS countries. Prioritization factors: current revenue markets, future market potential, manufacturing locations (to block competitors), investor requirements, competitor activity, enforcement capability. Startup strategy: typically file in USA and India initially; add Europe, China, Japan based on business development; defer or abandon applications in markets without commercial potential. National phase allows 30-31 months to assess market before committing major costs. Track all national phase deadlines carefully - missed deadline means loss of rights in that country. Consider patent prosecution highway (PPH) agreements to expedite prosecution using work from other offices.', '["Prioritize countries for national phase based on business strategy", "Calculate total cost for planned countries", "Create deadline management system", "Identify PPH opportunities for cost/time savings"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Country Prioritization Matrix", "National Phase Budget Planner", "Deadline Tracking Spreadsheet", "PPH Eligibility Checker"], "tools": ["WIPO National Phase Deadline Tool", "Multi-Jurisdiction Cost Calculator", "PPH Route Finder", "Regional Patent Guide"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_6_id, 26, 'Request for Examination Process', 'Examination does not begin automatically - a Request for Examination (RFE) must be filed using Form 18 within 48 months from the priority date or filing date, whichever is earlier. Failure to file RFE results in deemed withdrawal of application. Fee: Rs 4,000 for regular applicants, Rs 800 for startups. Strategic timing for RFE: early filing triggers faster examination (advantageous if prior art is minimal and quick grant desired); late filing defers examination costs and allows more time to assess commercial viability. Upon RFE, application enters examination queue. Regular examination timeline: 6-12 months for first examination report; expedited examination timeline: 1 month for first examination report. Expedited examination (Form 18A): available for startups under Rule 24C; fee Rs 8,000 (startup: Rs 1,600); requires DPIIT startup certificate; entire prosecution typically completed in 5-7 months. Other expedited categories: female applicants, small entities (with restrictions), government departments, eligible person under rule 24C. To prepare for examination: review prior art search results, anticipate likely objections, prepare response arguments, ensure specification supports all claims. After RFE filing, monitor application status on IPO e-Register for examination report upload. Set calendar reminder for response deadlines. Multiple applications can be queued for examination - consider business priorities when timing RFEs.', '["Determine optimal RFE timing for your application", "Prepare Form 18 or Form 18A as appropriate", "Set up monitoring for examination report", "Pre-prepare anticipated objection responses"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["RFE Timing Decision Matrix", "Form 18 Preparation Guide", "Form 18A Expedited Request Template", "Examination Preparation Checklist"], "tools": ["48-Month Deadline Calculator", "E-Register Status Monitor", "Expedited Eligibility Checker", "Response Preparation Tool"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_6_id, 27, 'Responding to First Examination Report (FER)', 'The First Examination Report (FER) contains examiner objections that must be addressed for grant. Common objections include: lack of novelty (Section 2(1)(l)) citing prior art; lack of inventive step (Section 2(1)(ja)); non-patentable subject matter (Section 3); clarity issues in claims; insufficient disclosure; unity of invention (multiple inventions in one application); formal defects. Response deadline: 6 months from FER date, extendable by 3 months on request with fee. Response filed using Form 13. Strategies by objection type: For novelty objection - distinguish from cited art by narrowing claims or arguing differences; for inventive step - argue unexpected results, technical advance, or non-obviousness of combination; for Section 3 objection - argue technical effect (software), enhanced efficacy (pharma), or proper claim drafting; for clarity - amend claims while maintaining scope. Response structure: address each objection point-by-point; provide amendments where needed; cite supporting evidence or arguments; request withdrawal of objection. Claim amendments must not add new matter and must be supported by original specification. Voluntary amendments can strengthen position. Professional patent agents typically charge Rs 15,000-50,000 for FER response depending on complexity. DIY response is possible but risky for complex objections. Maintain correspondence records and track amendment history. If objections cannot be overcome, consider divisional application for protectable aspects.', '["Analyze each FER objection thoroughly", "Develop response strategy for each objection", "Draft claim amendments if needed", "Prepare Form 13 response package"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["FER Analysis Worksheet", "Objection Response Template", "Claim Amendment Tracker", "Form 13 Preparation Checklist"], "tools": ["FER Response Generator", "Prior Art Distinction Helper", "Section 3 Compliance Checker", "Amendment Comparison Tool"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_6_id, 28, 'Claim Amendment Strategies', 'Claim amendments during prosecution require balancing scope protection with overcoming objections. Amendment types: narrowing claims (adding limitations to distinguish from prior art), clarifying claims (improving language without changing scope), correcting errors (obvious mistakes only), canceling claims, and adding dependent claims. Constraints: no new matter allowed - all amendments must be supported by original specification as filed; claims must fairly be based on description (Section 10(5)); cannot broaden claims after publication. Amendment strategies: use dependent claims as fallback positions; narrow independent claims while keeping broad dependent claims in reserve; distinguish from prior art by emphasizing novel features; address examiner concerns while preserving commercial coverage. For Section 3 objections (non-patentable): restructure claims to emphasize technical features; add method of making claims; include system claims with hardware elements. Voluntary amendments before examination can strengthen application. Amendments in response to FER should directly address objections. Track all amendments with rationale for prosecution history estoppel considerations (amendments may limit infringement arguments later). Request for hearing if written response insufficient. Post-grant amendments very limited - consider carefully during prosecution. Document claim scope evolution for portfolio management and licensing discussions.', '["Identify amendment options for each objection", "Ensure amendments have specification support", "Preserve maximum scope while addressing objections", "Document amendment rationale for records"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Amendment Options Matrix", "Specification Support Checker", "Claim Scope Comparison Template", "Amendment Rationale Log"], "tools": ["New Matter Validator", "Claim Breadth Analyzer", "Amendment Impact Calculator", "Prosecution History Manager"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_6_id, 29, 'Hearings and Controller Decisions', 'If written responses do not resolve objections, examiner may issue hearing notice. Hearing provides opportunity for oral arguments before Controller. Preparation: review all prosecution history, prepare argument outline, anticipate counter-arguments, bring supporting documentation. Hearing format: typically 30-60 minutes; applicant/agent presents arguments; Controller may ask questions; examiner may present position; decision issued later (days to weeks). Effective hearing arguments: focus on key issues (do not address resolved objections); cite relevant case law and Controller decisions; use visual aids for technical explanations; address examiner position directly; propose specific claim amendments if helpful. Common hearing outcomes: objections withdrawn and grant ordered; partial success with further amendments required; application refused (can appeal). Post-hearing procedure: if objections remain, Controller issues refusal order; applicant can file appeal to High Court (replaced IPAB since April 2021) within 3 months. Appeal costs significant (Rs 2-5 lakhs in legal fees typically); consider business case before appealing. Pre-grant opposition by third parties under Section 25(1) requires hearing where both parties present. Maintain hearing records including arguments presented and Controller observations. Hearing experience varies by IPO location and Controller - some are more receptive to oral arguments than others. Professional representation recommended for complex hearings.', '["Prepare comprehensive hearing argument outline", "Gather supporting documentation and precedents", "Practice presenting key technical distinctions", "Develop fallback positions if primary arguments fail"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Hearing Preparation Checklist", "Argument Outline Template", "Case Law Citation Matrix", "Fallback Position Document"], "tools": ["Controller Decision Database", "Hearing Scheduler", "Visual Aid Creator", "Argument Practice Framework"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_6_id, 30, 'Patent Grant and Certificate', 'When all objections are overcome, Controller issues intent to grant notification. Grant requirements: ensure all fees paid, all documents submitted, all objections resolved. Grant fee: no separate grant fee in India (covered by filing fees). Certificate of grant: issued after publication in Patent Office Journal; contains patent number, grant date, term (20 years from filing), claims as granted. Post-grant formalities: publication in Patent Office Journal (Part III); patent number assigned (IN-XXXXXXX format); certificate available on e-Register. Working statement requirement: Form 27 must be filed annually showing how patent is being commercially worked in India; due within 3 months of end of each calendar year; non-compliance can invite compulsory license request. Annual renewal fees: required from year 3 onwards; grace period of 6 months with additional fee; non-payment leads to lapse. First renewal (year 3-6): Rs 4,800 per year (startup: Rs 960). Set up renewal reminders immediately upon grant. Post-grant opposition: third parties can file opposition under Section 25(2) within 12 months of publication of grant; grounds include prior art, non-patentability, insufficient disclosure, wrongful obtaining, non-compliance with Section 8 (foreign filing information). Celebrate grant but remain vigilant - monitor for oppositions, maintain renewals, and update working statements. Certificate should be preserved carefully as official evidence of patent rights.', '["Verify all grant requirements are met", "Set up renewal reminder system", "Prepare first working statement (Form 27)", "Monitor for post-grant opposition filings"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Grant Verification Checklist", "Renewal Calendar Template", "Form 27 Working Statement Guide", "Post-Grant Monitoring Protocol"], "tools": ["Patent Certificate Viewer", "Renewal Fee Calculator", "Form 27 Generator", "Opposition Alert System"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_7_id, 31, 'Portfolio Strategy Development', 'A patent portfolio should align with business strategy, not just technical achievements. Portfolio purposes: block competitors (defensive patents covering key technology areas), enable freedom to operate (patents for cross-licensing leverage), attract investors (demonstrating innovation and barriers), generate revenue (licensing and litigation), and enhance company valuation (quantifiable IP assets). Strategy development: identify core technology areas for protection, map product roadmap to patent filing plan, assess competitive landscape for white spaces, determine geographic coverage based on markets, and set portfolio size targets. Portfolio types: defensive (broad coverage preventing workarounds), offensive (narrow but strong claims for enforcement), balanced (mix based on business needs). For startups, focus on quality over quantity - 3-5 strong patents in core technology more valuable than 20 weak patents. Filing velocity should match development pace and funding. Annual patent budget allocation: consider filing costs (Rs 10,000-50,000 per Indian application with prosecution), maintenance costs (increasing annually), and potential international expansion. Create patent committee with technical, business, and legal representation for filing decisions. Document portfolio strategy for investor presentations and M&A due diligence. Update strategy annually based on business evolution, competitive changes, and portfolio performance.', '["Define portfolio objectives aligned with business strategy", "Map product roadmap to filing plan", "Set annual portfolio size and budget targets", "Establish patent committee governance"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Portfolio Strategy Document", "Product-Patent Roadmap Template", "Annual IP Budget Planner", "Patent Committee Charter"], "tools": ["Portfolio Gap Analyzer", "Filing Priority Matrix", "Budget Allocation Tool", "Strategy Review Dashboard"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_7_id, 32, 'Continuation and Divisional Applications', 'Continuation and divisional applications extend portfolio protection from core filings. Divisional applications (Section 16): when examiner raises unity of invention objection, or proactively to protect different aspects; must be filed before grant of parent; claims different invention from same specification; maintains parent priority date; fee: same as new application. Continuation practice in India differs from US: India does not have continuation-in-part (CIP) concept; divisionals must claim matter disclosed in parent (no new matter); timing critical - divisionals only before parent grant. Strategic use: file divisionals for alternative embodiments, different claim types (method vs apparatus), or to preserve options during prosecution. Proactive divisional strategy: identify multiple inventions during drafting, file broad parent, file divisionals for specific applications before grant. Patent families: track related applications including parent, divisionals, and international equivalents; maintain consistent prosecution strategy; coordinate amendments to avoid inconsistencies. Cost management: divisionals have same fees as new applications; budget for potential divisionals in portfolio plan; prioritize based on commercial importance. Indian divisional practice requires careful timing monitoring - once parent grants, divisional window closes. Track parent application status vigilantly. Continuation-like protection through careful drafting of original specification with multiple embodiments enables future divisional options.', '["Identify divisional opportunities in pending applications", "Set up parent grant monitoring for timing", "Develop divisional filing strategy for key patents", "Create patent family tracking system"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Divisional Opportunity Assessment", "Parent Grant Alert System", "Patent Family Chart Template", "Divisional Strategy Matrix"], "tools": ["Unity of Invention Analyzer", "Grant Date Monitor", "Family Relationship Tracker", "Continuation Cost Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_7_id, 33, 'Patent Maintenance and Renewals', 'Indian patents require annual renewal fees to remain in force. Renewal schedule: fees due annually from year 3 through year 20; payment due before start of each year (based on filing date anniversary); grace period of 6 months with additional fee. Fee progression (2024 rates, large entity): Year 3-6: Rs 4,800/year; Year 7-10: Rs 12,000/year; Year 11-15: Rs 24,000/year; Year 16-20: Rs 80,000/year. Startup discount: 80% reduction on all renewal fees. Total lifetime maintenance cost: approximately Rs 5.8 lakhs (large entity) or Rs 1.16 lakhs (startup) over 20 years. Payment process: Form 4 with fee through e-filing portal; receipt confirmation essential; maintain payment records. Lapse and restoration: if renewal missed, patent lapses; restoration possible within 18 months of lapse under Section 60 with fees and Form 15; restoration not guaranteed. Portfolio maintenance decisions: annually review portfolio to identify patents for continued maintenance vs abandonment; factors include commercial relevance, competitive blocking value, licensing potential, and remaining term. Abandonment savings: discontinuing non-essential patents saves maintenance costs; document abandonment decisions; consider offering for sale before abandonment. International maintenance: each country has different renewal schedules and fees; use international docketing system for deadline management. Set up automated renewal reminders 6 months and 3 months before due date. Work with reliable renewal service for international patents to avoid missed deadlines.', '["Create patent renewal calendar with all deadlines", "Implement annual portfolio review process", "Calculate lifetime maintenance costs per patent", "Establish abandonment decision criteria"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Renewal Calendar Template", "Portfolio Review Checklist", "Maintenance Cost Calculator", "Abandonment Decision Matrix"], "tools": ["Renewal Deadline Tracker", "Fee Payment Portal Guide", "Restoration Process Guide", "Portfolio Optimization Tool"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_7_id, 34, 'Patent Valuation Methods', 'Patent valuation is essential for licensing negotiations, M&A transactions, financing, and portfolio management decisions. Valuation approaches: Cost approach - total investment in developing and protecting the patent (R&D costs, filing costs, prosecution costs); useful for early-stage patents without revenue; typically undervalues commercially successful patents. Market approach - comparable transaction analysis; find similar patent sales or licenses; adjust for technology area, claim scope, remaining term, and market conditions; challenged by limited public data on patent transactions. Income approach - discounted cash flow of expected future revenue from patent; requires revenue projections from product sales, licensing royalties, or cost savings; most relevant for commercially proven patents; factors include market size, market share, profit margin, patent contribution factor, and discount rate. Relief from royalty method - calculate royalties saved by owning vs licensing the technology; use industry standard royalty rates (0.5%-8% depending on industry); multiply by projected revenue and discount to present value. Indian context: patent valuation gaining importance for bank financing (IP collateralized loans), startup valuations, and government grants. NASSCOM-DSCI framework provides guidance on IP valuation for Indian startups. For investor discussions, present range of valuations using multiple methods. Update valuations annually as commercial evidence accumulates.', '["Value core patents using multiple methods", "Document valuation assumptions and data sources", "Create valuation update schedule", "Prepare investor-ready valuation summary"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Cost Approach Valuation Template", "Market Approach Comparable Analysis", "DCF Valuation Model", "Relief from Royalty Calculator"], "tools": ["Royalty Rate Database", "DCF Calculation Tool", "Comparable Transaction Finder", "Valuation Summary Generator"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_7_id, 35, 'Portfolio Analytics and Optimization', 'Data-driven portfolio management enables strategic decision-making. Key metrics to track: portfolio size and growth rate, filing success rate (applications to grants), prosecution efficiency (time and cost to grant), geographic coverage alignment with markets, technology coverage alignment with products, citation analysis (forward citations indicate influence), and competitive position (patent share in technology area). Portfolio analytics tools: IPO e-Register for Indian patents status, commercial tools like PatSnap, Innography, Orbit for comprehensive analysis, and free tools like Lens.org and Google Patents for basic analysis. Portfolio optimization actions: identify underperforming patents for abandonment, find gaps requiring new filings, discover licensing opportunities from unused patents, and recognize acquisition targets to fill gaps. Competitive benchmarking: compare portfolio size, filing trends, technology focus, and geographic coverage with competitors; identify their strategic direction from filing patterns. Investor reporting: create quarterly portfolio dashboard showing filing activity, grant rate, portfolio growth, and competitive position. Portfolio reviews: conduct formal annual review with technical, business, and legal stakeholders; align portfolio with updated business strategy; reallocate budget based on performance. For startups, focus on quality metrics (grant rate, claim scope, commercial coverage) over quantity. Build analytics capability as portfolio grows - spreadsheet tracking for small portfolios, specialized tools for larger ones.', '["Define portfolio metrics and tracking system", "Conduct competitive benchmarking analysis", "Identify optimization opportunities", "Create portfolio reporting dashboard"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Portfolio Metrics Dashboard", "Competitive Benchmark Template", "Optimization Action Plan", "Quarterly Portfolio Report"], "tools": ["Portfolio Analytics Platform", "Citation Analysis Tool", "Gap Identification System", "Competitor Tracking Dashboard"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_8_id, 36, 'Patent Licensing Fundamentals', 'Licensing grants rights to use patented technology in exchange for consideration. License types: exclusive (one licensee, licensor cannot use), sole (one licensee, licensor can use), non-exclusive (multiple licensees possible), and field-of-use limited (restricted to specific application areas). Key terms: territory (geographic scope), field of use (application limitations), duration (term of license), sublicensing rights, improvement ownership, and termination provisions. Compensation models: running royalty (percentage of sales, typically 1-8% depending on industry), paid-up/lump sum (one-time payment), milestone payments (upon achievement of development/commercial goals), hybrid (upfront plus running royalty), and cross-license (exchange of patent rights). Indian considerations: licensing agreements should be in writing and ideally registered with Patent Office under Section 68-70 for enforceability against third parties; registration fee Rs 4,000 (startup: Rs 800); license can be exclusive or non-exclusive; territory can be limited to India or include other countries. Tax implications: royalty payments may attract TDS and GST; transfer pricing considerations for related party licenses; proper documentation essential. Licensing strategy: determine which patents to license (non-core, non-competing uses), identify potential licensees (market research, inbound inquiries), set licensing objectives (revenue, market expansion, relationship building), and prepare licensing package (patent list, value proposition, standard terms).', '["Identify patents suitable for licensing", "Research potential licensees in target fields", "Develop licensing term preferences", "Create licensing opportunity package"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["License Type Comparison Matrix", "Royalty Calculation Template", "Licensee Identification Framework", "Licensing Package Outline"], "tools": ["Royalty Rate Benchmarking Tool", "Licensee Research Database", "License Registration Guide", "Tax Implication Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_8_id, 37, 'Licensing Negotiation and Agreement', 'Successful licensing requires structured negotiation and comprehensive agreements. Negotiation preparation: understand your BATNA (best alternative to negotiated agreement), research licensee business and needs, determine your minimum acceptable terms, and prepare negotiation strategy. Negotiation process: start with non-binding term sheet; iterate on key terms before full agreement; involve legal counsel for complex deals; document all agreed points. Agreement structure: recitals (background and purpose), definitions (key terms), grant clause (specific rights licensed), limitations (field of use, territory, sublicensing), consideration (payment terms), representations and warranties, indemnification, audit rights, term and termination, and dispute resolution. Critical clauses for licensor: minimum royalty or guaranteed payments (floor regardless of sales), audit rights with adequate frequency, infringement enforcement cooperation, quality control provisions, and termination for material breach. Critical clauses for licensee: clear scope definition, protection against licensor competing, most-favored-licensee clause, and improvement rights. Indian law aspects: Indian Contract Act 1872 governs; arbitration clause recommended with seat in India; stamp duty applicable based on agreement value and state. Registration with Indian Patent Office: Section 68 requires registration within 6 months; unregistered license may not be enforceable against third parties. Have agreements reviewed by IP counsel before signing.', '["Prepare negotiation strategy with BATNA analysis", "Draft non-binding term sheet", "Review critical agreement clauses", "Plan for registration post-signing"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["BATNA Analysis Worksheet", "Term Sheet Template", "License Agreement Checklist", "Agreement Clause Library"], "tools": ["Negotiation Planning Tool", "Agreement Drafting Guide", "Stamp Duty Calculator", "Registration Process Guide"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_8_id, 38, 'Patent Sale and Assignment', 'Patent sale (assignment) transfers ownership permanently. Reasons to sell: non-core patents (not aligned with current business), need for capital (monetize IP assets), strategic exit (part of M&A), and portfolio optimization (reduce maintenance costs). Valuation for sale: use income, market, and cost approaches; obtain independent valuation for significant sales; consider tax implications in pricing. Finding buyers: patent brokers and intermediaries (charge 15-30% commission), direct approach to companies using similar technology, patent aggregators (defensive or offensive), online patent marketplaces, and auction platforms. Assignment process in India: assignment deed in writing (Section 68); must be registered with Patent Office using Form 16; registration fee Rs 4,000 per patent (startup: Rs 800); unregistered assignment not valid against third parties. Assignment deed contents: parties, patent identification, consideration, representations, warranties (validity, no encumbrances, no pending claims), and indemnification. Tax implications: sale proceeds taxable as capital gains; holding period determines short-term vs long-term treatment; indexation benefit available for long-term. Seller considerations: retain rights for existing products (license back), warranty limitations, and indemnity caps. Buyer due diligence: verify ownership chain, check for encumbrances (prior licenses, security interests), confirm renewal status, and assess validity risks. Consider exclusive license as alternative to sale - maintains ownership while monetizing.', '["Identify patents for potential sale", "Prepare valuation for sale candidates", "Research buyer options and channels", "Draft assignment documentation"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Sale Candidate Evaluation Matrix", "Assignment Deed Template", "Due Diligence Checklist (Buyer)", "Tax Implication Analysis"], "tools": ["Patent Marketplace Directory", "Assignment Registration Guide", "Form 16 Preparation Tool", "Capital Gains Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_8_id, 39, 'Strategic Licensing and Cross-Licensing', 'Strategic licensing uses patents for business objectives beyond direct revenue. Cross-licensing: mutual license between parties to access each other patent portfolios; common in complex technology industries (semiconductors, telecommunications); balancing payment based on relative portfolio value; reduces litigation risk and enables market freedom. Standard-essential patent (SEP) licensing: patents essential to practice technical standards (5G, WiFi, video codecs); requires licensing on FRAND (Fair, Reasonable, and Non-Discriminatory) terms; SEP declarations filed with standards bodies; royalty stacking concerns with multiple SEP holders. Technology partnerships: patents as currency for R&D collaborations; joint development agreements with IP sharing provisions; university-industry partnerships with exclusive license rights. Defensive aggregation: joining patent pools (Defensive Patent License, LOT Network) that require members to license to each other; protection against patent trolls; reduces litigation risk across the ecosystem. Indian context: SEPs relevant for India telecommunications market as 5G rolls out; cross-licensing common in pharmaceutical industry for drug combinations; government may compel licensing under Sections 84-92 if patented invention not worked in India. Strategic licensing requires understanding both IP and business relationship - frame discussions around mutual value creation. Document all licensing relationships centrally for portfolio management.', '["Identify cross-licensing opportunities with key players", "Assess SEP relevance for your technology", "Evaluate defensive aggregation membership", "Develop strategic partnership framework"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Cross-License Negotiation Framework", "SEP Declaration Guide", "Partnership IP Terms Template", "Defensive Aggregation Comparison"], "tools": ["Cross-License Valuation Tool", "FRAND Rate Calculator", "Standards Body Directory", "Patent Pool Database"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_8_id, 40, 'Patent-Backed Financing', 'Patents can serve as collateral for debt financing, providing capital without equity dilution. Indian framework: patents can be pledged as security under the Indian Contract Act 1872; security interest created through registered agreement; in case of default, secured creditor has priority. Banks offering IP-backed lending in India: limited but growing, including SBI, Bank of Baroda, and some private banks; typically combined with other collateral; valuation by approved IP valuer required. IP financing options: traditional bank loan with IP collateral (lower interest rates), venture debt with IP security interest, sale-leaseback (sell patents, license back), royalty financing (advance against future royalties), and IP securitization (for large portfolios). Preparing for IP financing: obtain independent IP valuation from approved valuer, demonstrate commercial application and revenue potential, maintain patent in good standing (renewals current), show ownership chain and no encumbrances, and present litigation-ready enforcement capability. Documentation: loan agreement, security agreement creating charge on patents, registration with Patent Office under Section 68, and Companies Act charge registration with ROC (for companies). Risks: default leads to patent seizure; restrictive covenants may limit licensing; valuation challenges may reduce lending amount. IP financing is emerging in India - government initiatives through SIDBI and specialized IP funds are improving access. Patent quality and commercial proof significantly impact financing terms.', '["Assess patents suitable for collateral", "Obtain professional IP valuation", "Research IP financing options available", "Prepare financing documentation package"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["IP Financing Readiness Checklist", "Valuation Documentation Package", "Security Agreement Template", "Lender Comparison Matrix"], "tools": ["IP Valuer Directory (India)", "Financing Option Calculator", "Security Registration Guide", "ROC Charge Filing Tool"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_9_id, 41, 'Infringement Monitoring Systems', 'Proactive infringement monitoring identifies unauthorized use of patented technology. Monitoring approaches: product surveillance (track competitor product launches, review specifications and teardowns), patent landscape monitoring (watch competitor filings for potential design-arounds), market monitoring (trade shows, industry publications, online marketplaces), and supply chain monitoring (identify unauthorized manufacturers). Monitoring tools: set up Google Alerts for technology keywords; subscribe to industry publications and news; monitor product listings on Amazon, Flipkart, IndiaMART; attend relevant trade shows; conduct periodic competitor product analysis. Technical analysis: when potential infringement identified, obtain product samples; conduct detailed technical analysis against claim elements; document analysis with photographs, measurements, and testing results; engage technical expert if needed. Creating claim charts: map each claim element to allegedly infringing product feature; note exact product component corresponding to each limitation; identify any missing elements (no infringement if element missing). Indian market monitoring specifics: watch for infringing imports at customs using IP recordation (register with Customs under IPR Rules 2007); monitor manufacturing clusters in your industry; track government tenders requiring patent-compliant products. Monitoring costs: balance comprehensiveness with budget; focus on core patents and key markets; use combination of automated alerts and periodic manual review. Document all monitoring activities and findings for potential enforcement.', '["Set up automated monitoring alerts", "Identify key competitors and products to watch", "Establish claim chart analysis process", "Register patents with Indian Customs"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Monitoring Protocol Template", "Claim Chart Framework", "Product Analysis Checklist", "Customs Recordation Guide"], "tools": ["Alert Setup Tool", "Competitor Tracking Dashboard", "Technical Analysis Documentation", "Customs IPR Portal"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_9_id, 42, 'Infringement Analysis and Opinion', 'Before enforcement action, rigorous infringement analysis is essential. Literal infringement: each element of patent claim must be present in accused product; even one missing element means no literal infringement. Doctrine of equivalents: in India, limited application; element may infringe if it performs substantially same function in substantially same way to achieve substantially same result; constrained by prosecution history. Inducement and contributory infringement: Section 48 covers direct infringement; inducement (actively encouraging infringement) and contributory infringement (providing components specifically for infringement) less developed in Indian law. Opinion process: engage qualified patent attorney; provide detailed product information and patent claims; attorney conducts element-by-element analysis; formal infringement opinion issued. Opinion purposes: basis for enforcement decision, supports good faith in litigation, and helps assess strength of position. Infringement analysis should also consider: validity risks (would claims survive challenge?), design-around possibilities (can infringer easily modify product?), damages quantum (what are the losses/profits?), and enforcement cost vs recovery (economic justification). Non-infringement opinions: obtain when developing new products; demonstrates good faith if later accused; helps identify design modifications to avoid infringement. For startups, formal opinions from reputable IP firms strengthen position with investors and potential licensees. Balance opinion costs against value of decision clarity.', '["Conduct preliminary infringement analysis in-house", "Engage patent attorney for formal opinion if warranted", "Document evidence supporting infringement", "Assess validity and design-around risks"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Preliminary Infringement Checklist", "Attorney Engagement Template", "Evidence Documentation Guide", "Risk Assessment Matrix"], "tools": ["Claim Mapping Tool", "Element Analysis Spreadsheet", "Validity Risk Checker", "Opinion Request Template"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_9_id, 43, 'Cease and Desist Strategy', 'Before litigation, cease and desist (C&D) correspondence often resolves infringement. C&D objectives: stop infringement immediately, preserve evidence of infringement, open negotiation for license, document willful infringement for enhanced damages, and demonstrate enforcement intent. C&D letter contents: identify patent(s) infringed, describe infringing activity, demand cessation within specified timeframe (typically 15-30 days), offer licensing discussion, and reserve all legal rights. Strategic considerations: timing (early notice vs building evidence), tone (aggressive vs cooperative), recipient (infringer directly, legal department, executives), and publicity (private communication vs public statement). Response possibilities: compliance (stops infringement), license negotiation, denial of infringement, validity challenge, or silence/continued infringement. Indian context: send C&D through registered post with acknowledgment due; maintain copies of all correspondence; consider involving advocate for formal legal notice under advocates letterhead. Follow-up: if no response within deadline, follow up in writing; document continued infringement; assess litigation readiness. Risks of C&D: infringer may file declaratory judgment action first; letter may be used against you if claims weak; may alert infringer to modify product. Strategic alternatives: offer license directly without C&D; acquire evidence through market purchase first; coordinate with other patentees if common infringer. C&D is often first step - plan for escalation if unsuccessful.', '["Analyze strategic timing for C&D communication", "Draft clear and comprehensive C&D letter", "Prepare for possible infringer responses", "Document evidence before sending notice"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Cease and Desist Letter Template (India)", "Response Protocol Guide", "Evidence Preservation Checklist", "Escalation Decision Matrix"], "tools": ["Registered Post Tracking", "Legal Notice Format Guide", "Response Timeline Tracker", "Negotiation Preparation Tool"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_9_id, 44, 'Patent Litigation in India', 'When negotiation fails, litigation enforces patent rights. Jurisdiction: High Court having jurisdiction over infringer location or where cause of action arises; Delhi, Bombay, Madras High Courts have IP divisions with specialized judges. Suit filing: plaint (complaint) detailing patents, infringement, and reliefs sought; court fees based on relief value; plaintiff must prove ownership, infringement, and validity if challenged. Typical timeline: ex parte interim injunction possible within days; notice and opposition to interim relief (weeks); full trial (2-5 years for complex cases); appeals add further time. Relief types: permanent injunction (stop infringement), interim injunction (immediate but temporary), damages (compensatory based on loss), accounts of profits (infringer disgorgement), delivery up (surrender infringing products), and costs. Litigation costs: court fees, attorney fees (Rs 5-50 lakhs+ for full litigation), expert witness fees, evidence collection costs. Success factors: strong patent claims that clearly read on product, good evidence of infringement, patent validity (anticipate invalidity defense), documented damages, and credible expert witnesses. Validity challenges: defendant almost always challenges patent validity; grounds mirror grounds for revocation under Section 64; patent holder must be prepared to defend validity. Consider mediation: courts encourage mediation; can resolve faster and cheaper than full trial; preserves business relationships. Contingency or partial contingency arrangements possible with some IP litigation firms.', '["Assess litigation readiness and economics", "Identify appropriate forum and counsel", "Prepare evidence package for filing", "Anticipate and prepare for validity challenge"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Litigation Decision Matrix", "Counsel Selection Criteria", "Evidence Compilation Checklist", "Validity Defense Preparation"], "tools": ["Court Fee Calculator", "IP Litigation Counsel Directory", "Case Timeline Estimator", "Damages Calculation Framework"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_9_id, 45, 'Alternative Dispute Resolution for Patents', 'ADR offers faster, cost-effective patent dispute resolution. Arbitration: private adjudication by chosen arbitrator; Arbitration and Conciliation Act 1996 governs; parties can agree to arbitrate infringement and validity disputes; typically faster than court (12-18 months); confidential proceedings; limited appeal. Mediation: facilitated negotiation by neutral mediator; non-binding unless parties agree to settlement; can preserve business relationships; courts may refer cases to mediation under Section 89 CPC. International arbitration: for cross-border disputes; WIPO Arbitration and Mediation Center specializes in IP; ICC, LCIA also handle IP disputes; arbitral award enforceable under New York Convention. Patent dispute-specific considerations: technical experts as arbitrators (understand technology better than generalist judges), expedited procedures available, combine mediation and arbitration (med-arb), and draft arbitration clauses in license agreements proactively. ADR limitations: no interim relief power (must approach courts), no binding precedent created, limited discovery compared to litigation, and difficult if third parties involved. Cost comparison: mediation cheapest (Rs 50,000-2 lakhs typically), arbitration moderate (Rs 5-20 lakhs), litigation highest (Rs 10-50+ lakhs). Indian startup context: ADR appropriate for disputes with licensing partners, resolution of validity questions before full litigation, and international disputes where enforcement in multiple countries needed. Include ADR clauses in all patent-related agreements.', '["Include ADR clauses in patent agreements", "Identify appropriate ADR mechanism for dispute type", "Research IP-specialized arbitrators and mediators", "Prepare ADR strategy as alternative to litigation"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Arbitration Clause Template", "Mediation Agreement Format", "ADR Provider Comparison", "Settlement Framework"], "tools": ["WIPO ADR Center Guide", "Indian Arbitration Council Directory", "ADR Cost Calculator", "Settlement Negotiation Framework"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_10_id, 46, 'Trade Secret Law in India', 'India has no dedicated trade secret statute, but protection exists through multiple legal doctrines. Legal basis: Indian Contract Act 1872 (breach of confidentiality agreements), common law principles of equity (breach of confidence), Information Technology Act 2000 (for electronic information), and Indian Penal Code (criminal breach of trust). Trade secret elements: information that derives economic value from being secret, is not generally known in the industry, and is subject to reasonable secrecy measures. Indian courts have recognized trade secret protection in key cases: John Richard Brady v. Chemical Process Equipments (1987) established confidential information protection; Burlington Home Shopping v. Rajnish Chibber (1995) extended protection to customer data; and recent cases have protected manufacturing processes, algorithms, and business methodologies. Information that qualifies: manufacturing processes, formulas, recipes, customer lists, pricing data, marketing strategies, algorithms, and proprietary methods. Information that does not qualify: publicly available information, general skills and knowledge of employees, and information not kept confidential. India context: enforcement through civil suits for injunction and damages; criminal action possible under IPC Section 405/406 for breach of trust; no statutory damages like US Defend Trade Secrets Act. Trade secrets can protect information indefinitely unlike patents' 20-year limit - Coca-Cola formula is the classic example. However, protection lost if secret becomes public through any means, including reverse engineering.', '["Identify information qualifying as trade secrets", "Understand legal basis for protection in India", "Review relevant court decisions for your industry", "Assess current confidentiality measures"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Trade Secret Identification Checklist", "Legal Basis Summary Document", "Case Law Reference Guide", "Confidentiality Assessment Form"], "tools": ["Trade Secret Classification Tool", "Legal Protection Mapper", "Case Database (Indian IP)", "Secrecy Measures Evaluator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_10_id, 47, 'Implementing Trade Secret Protection', 'Effective trade secret protection requires systematic measures across organization. Identification and classification: document all trade secrets; classify by sensitivity level (confidential, highly confidential, restricted); assign ownership and access rights. Physical security: restricted access areas; visitor protocols; secure storage for sensitive documents; clean desk policy. Technical security: access controls and authentication; encryption for sensitive data; secure communication channels; activity logging and monitoring; data loss prevention systems. Contractual protection: confidentiality agreements (NDA) with all employees, contractors, visitors; specific trade secret clauses in employment agreements; post-employment confidentiality obligations (note: non-compete clauses unenforceable in India under Section 27 of Contract Act, but confidentiality continues). Employee measures: onboarding training on confidentiality obligations; regular reminders; exit interviews with return of materials and confidentiality reminder; separation of duties so no one person has complete secret. Documentation: maintain evidence of secrecy measures; document who has access to what; keep records of confidentiality training; photograph secure areas and controls. Third-party relationships: NDA before any disclosure; limit information shared to what is necessary; mark documents confidential; track disclosures made. Regular audits: annually review trade secret inventory; assess effectiveness of security measures; identify gaps and improve. These measures serve dual purpose: prevent leaks and demonstrate reasonable efforts for legal enforcement.', '["Create trade secret inventory with classification", "Implement physical and technical security measures", "Deploy comprehensive confidentiality agreements", "Establish regular audit protocol"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Trade Secret Inventory Template", "Security Measures Checklist", "NDA Template (India Compliant)", "Audit Protocol Document"], "tools": ["Access Control System Guide", "Encryption Implementation Guide", "NDA Management System", "Audit Scheduling Tool"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_10_id, 48, 'Employee Confidentiality Management', 'Employees are primary risk and primary protection for trade secrets. Hiring practices: background checks on sensitive roles; reference checks for prior confidentiality issues; evaluate information they might bring from previous employers (avoid receiving third-party trade secrets). Onboarding: confidentiality agreement signed before access to sensitive information; training on confidentiality obligations and consequences of breach; clear documentation of what information is confidential; acknowledgment of receipt of company policies. During employment: need-to-know access only; regular confidentiality reminders; monitoring for policy compliance; reporting channels for suspected breaches. Sensitive roles: additional agreements for R&D, manufacturing, and customer-facing roles; restricted access periods after significant project completion. Exit management: exit interview reviewing obligations; collection of all company materials (physical and digital); remind of continuing confidentiality obligations; formal acknowledgment signed. Note on restrictive covenants: post-employment non-compete clauses are void under Section 27 of Indian Contract Act; however, confidentiality obligations continue indefinitely; non-solicitation of customers/employees generally enforceable if reasonable. Former employee monitoring: cannot prevent using general skills, but watch for specific trade secret use; be prepared to act quickly if misappropriation suspected. Garden leave: placing employees on paid leave during notice period restricts access during transition; increasingly common for sensitive roles in India. Document all measures for enforcement evidence.', '["Review and update employment confidentiality agreements", "Implement comprehensive onboarding protocol", "Establish exit interview process", "Create monitoring system for high-risk departures"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Employee Confidentiality Agreement", "Onboarding Training Checklist", "Exit Interview Protocol", "Post-Employment Monitoring Guide"], "tools": ["Background Check Process", "Training Documentation System", "Exit Management Tracker", "Garden Leave Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_10_id, 49, 'Trade Secret Enforcement', 'When misappropriation occurs, swift action is critical. Immediate steps upon discovery: secure evidence (do not alert suspected party); engage legal counsel experienced in trade secret matters; assess scope of misappropriation; identify recipients of misappropriated information; preserve all relevant communications and documents. Legal options: civil suit for injunction (stop further use/disclosure) and damages; interim injunction critical - approach High Court urgently; criminal complaint under IPC Sections 405/406 for breach of trust, Section 420 for cheating. Civil suit elements: prove information qualifies as trade secret; prove defendant had duty of confidence (employment, NDA, received in confidence); prove breach of confidence (actual or threatened); demonstrate harm from misappropriation. Remedies available: injunction (permanent and interim) restraining use and disclosure; damages for actual loss; account of profits gained by misappropriator; delivery up or destruction of materials containing trade secret; costs. Evidence challenges: proving what was taken can be difficult; forensic examination of devices may be needed; discovery/disclosure orders can compel production. Timing: act immediately - delay weakens injunction request and may indicate information not truly valuable. Indian courts: specialized IP divisions in Delhi, Bombay, Madras High Courts; experienced judges can grant ex parte interim orders within days. Balance enforcement against business relationship considerations - sometimes negotiated resolution preserves long-term value.', '["Create incident response protocol for suspected misappropriation", "Identify specialized legal counsel for trade secrets", "Establish evidence preservation procedures", "Understand injunction process in relevant High Court"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Incident Response Protocol", "Evidence Preservation Checklist", "Legal Action Decision Matrix", "Injunction Application Guide"], "tools": ["Digital Forensics Guide", "Counsel Directory (Trade Secrets)", "Court Procedure Navigator", "Damages Calculation Framework"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_10_id, 50, 'Trade Secret and Patent Strategy Integration', 'Optimal IP strategy combines trade secrets and patents based on nature of innovation. Decision framework for each innovation: Can it be reverse-engineered from commercial product? (if yes, patent preferred); Is 20-year exclusivity sufficient? (if no, trade secret may extend protection); Does public disclosure enable beneficial patent claims? (if not, trade secret may be appropriate); What are enforcement capabilities and needs? Integration strategies: patent the external/visible innovation, trade secret the manufacturing process; file patents but protect specific parameters as trade secrets within patented method; use trade secrets during development, file patents when commercializing. Combined protection example: software system patented for method/system claims (technical effect), trade secret protection for specific algorithms and training data (implementation details), copyright for code expression. Portfolio consideration: trade secrets require ongoing protection investment (security, agreements, training); patents require prosecution and maintenance fees but provide 20-year documented right. Risk balancing: trade secret loss is irreversible if information becomes public; patent scope may narrow during prosecution; independent discovery defeats trade secrets but not patents. For startups: use trade secrets for early-stage protection while building patent portfolio; transition to patents as commercial proof accumulates; maintain trade secrets for supporting know-how around patented inventions. Document trade secret protection measures even for matter related to patents - demonstrates overall IP management sophistication to investors and acquirers.', '["Evaluate each innovation against protection criteria", "Develop integrated IP strategy combining patents and trade secrets", "Document trade secret measures for patent-related information", "Create ongoing IP strategy review process"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Patent vs Trade Secret Decision Framework", "Integrated IP Strategy Template", "Documentation Protocol", "Strategy Review Checklist"], "tools": ["Innovation Assessment Tool", "Protection Comparison Calculator", "IP Portfolio Tracker", "Strategy Review Dashboard"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_11_id, 51, 'Design Registration in India', 'The Designs Act 2000 protects novel and original aesthetic features applied to articles. Design vs patent: designs protect appearance (shape, configuration, pattern, ornamentation, color); patents protect function. Registrable designs must be: new (not published or used before filing), original (not known or not obvious simulation), applied to article of manufacture, and visible in normal use (not purely functional). Non-registrable: designs contrary to public order/morality, functional features dictated solely by function (spares exception removed in 2001 amendment), flags and emblems, and scandalous matter. Registration process: application (Form 1) with representations (four views minimum) filed at Design Wing of Patent Office; examination for formalities and registrability; registration typically within 3-9 months; no substantive examination like patents. Fees: Rs 1,000 for small entity (includes startups), Rs 4,000 for others. Protection: 10 years initially, renewable for 5 years (total 15 years); protects against unauthorized making, importing, selling, or stocking the design. Classification: Locarno Classification used; proper classification important for search and examination. Comparison to patents: designs much faster and cheaper to obtain; no examination of prior art (but can be invalidated later); narrower protection (specific appearance vs broader concept). Strategic use: design registration for product appearance while patenting underlying technology; multiple designs for product variations; building design portfolio for product lines.', '["Identify product features suitable for design registration", "Prepare design representations (photographs/drawings)", "Determine correct Locarno classification", "File design application through e-filing portal"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Design Registration Checklist", "Representation Specifications Guide", "Locarno Classification Finder", "Application Form 1 Template"], "tools": ["Design e-Filing Portal", "Locarno Classification Browser", "Design Fee Calculator", "Representation Quality Checker"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_11_id, 52, 'Design Prosecution and Enforcement', 'Design registration process is streamlined but requires attention to detail. Examination: Design Office examines for formalities, proper representation, and prima facie registrability; objections issued for deficiencies; response required within prescribed time; registration certificate issued after objections cleared. Representation quality: crucial for protection scope; show all visible features clearly; include multiple views (front, back, sides, top, perspective); use consistent scale and presentation; broken lines show disclaimed matter. Common objections: representations unclear, incorrect article name, wrong classification, prior publication found, and formal deficiencies in application. Amendment: limited amendment possible before registration; representations cannot be fundamentally changed. Design rights: exclusive right to apply design to article and import/sell articles bearing the design; no defense of independent creation (unlike copyright). Infringement: design registration creates presumption of validity; infringement if design applied to same or similar article without license; test: whether design produces same visual impression on informed user. Enforcement: civil suit in District Court or High Court; remedies include injunction, damages, account of profits, and delivery up; also criminal penalty possible (Section 22 - up to Rs 50,000 fine). Cancellation: any person can file cancellation petition (Form 8) on grounds including prior publication, lack of novelty, or not a design under the Act; cancellation petition can be filed any time during registration validity. Build enforcement-ready file with use evidence and design evolution documentation.', '["Monitor examination status and respond to objections promptly", "Maintain quality representation standards", "Document design use for enforcement evidence", "Prepare for potential cancellation challenges"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Objection Response Template", "Representation Quality Standards", "Design Use Documentation Guide", "Cancellation Defense Preparation"], "tools": ["Design Status Tracker", "Objection Analysis Tool", "Evidence Compilation System", "Cancellation Process Guide"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_11_id, 53, 'International Design Protection', 'International design protection follows different routes than PCT for patents. Hague System: India joined the Hague Agreement (Geneva Act) in 2019; single international application designating up to 100 countries; file through WIPO or through Indian Design Office as Office of Origin; fees vary by country designated; 6-month publication by WIPO then protection in designated countries subject to their national examination. National filings: traditional route filing separately in each country; Paris Convention provides 6-month priority from first design filing (shorter than 12 months for patents). Key jurisdictions: USA (design patents, 15-year term, examination required), EU (registered community design, 25-year term, no examination), UK (registered design, 25-year term), China (design patents, 15-year term, examination), and Japan (design registration, 25-year term). Hague advantages: single application, single fee payment, centralized management, 6-12 month time/cost savings compared to national filings. Hague limitations: some countries not members (China joined in 2022, becoming significant); novelty grace period varies by country; still need local counsel for some countries. Strategic considerations: design protection important for consumer products, fashion, furniture, electronics, automotive; coordinate with patent protection for full coverage; consider design registration before product launch (novelty requirement). India Hague implementation: Indian Design Office accepts applications as Office of Origin; Rs 2,000 fee (Indian portion); examination and registration follows same process as national applications.', '["Assess international design protection needs", "Evaluate Hague vs national filing routes", "Identify priority jurisdictions for design protection", "Coordinate design and patent filing strategies"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["International Design Strategy Template", "Hague vs National Comparison Matrix", "Jurisdiction Priority Assessment", "Coordinated Filing Timeline"], "tools": ["WIPO Hague Portal", "International Fee Calculator", "Novelty Period Tracker", "Multi-Jurisdiction Deadline Manager"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_11_id, 54, 'Utility Models (Petty Patents)', 'Utility models (not available in India) provide lighter-weight protection for incremental innovations in many countries. Utility model characteristics: lower inventive step requirement than patents; shorter term (6-15 years depending on country); faster grant (no substantive examination in most countries); lower costs; limited to physical inventions (no methods/processes typically). Countries with utility model systems: China (very popular - millions filed annually), Germany (Gebrauchsmuster), Japan, South Korea, Australia (innovation patents - being phased out), Brazil, and most of Latin America. Strategic use for Indian startups: consider utility model filings in key markets alongside patents; useful for incremental innovations that may not meet patent inventive step; faster protection while patent pending; cost-effective protection for shorter commercial cycles. China utility models: 10-year term; no examination (grant within months); high invalidation rate but provides initial deterrent; very common strategy for consumer products. Germany utility models: 10-year term; no examination; can branch from patent application; useful for quick protection. Conversion and branching: some countries allow conversion between patent and utility model; German utility model can be branched from pending patent. Cost comparison: Chinese utility model approximately $500-1,000 total; German utility model approximately $500-800; vs patent applications costing $3,000-10,000+. Limitations: no utility model in USA, UK, India (design registration is alternative); may be difficult to enforce; perceived as lower quality. For mechanical and electronic products with rapid market cycles, utility models provide valuable protection layer.', '["Evaluate utility model strategy for international markets", "Identify innovations suitable for utility model protection", "Calculate cost/benefit vs patent protection", "Plan coordinated utility model and patent filings"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Utility Model Decision Framework", "Country Comparison Chart", "Cost-Benefit Analysis Template", "Coordinated Filing Strategy"], "tools": ["Utility Model Country Guide", "China Utility Model Guide", "Germany Gebrauchsmuster Process", "Cost Comparison Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_11_id, 55, 'Integrated Design and Patent Strategy', 'Comprehensive IP strategy integrates design and patent protection for maximum coverage. Layered protection approach: patent protects functional innovation (method, mechanism, technical features); design protects aesthetic innovation (shape, appearance, ornamentation); trademark protects brand elements; copyright protects creative expression (documentation, software, artwork). Example - smartphone: utility patents for technical innovations (processor architecture, antenna design, software methods); design patents/registrations for physical appearance (shape, screen layout, icon arrangement); trademarks for brand name and logo; copyright for software code and user interface elements. Timing considerations: design registration before product launch (novelty requirement); patent filing before public disclosure (absolute novelty in India); coordinate timing to maintain options. Portfolio building: identify protectable elements in each product; file patents for core innovations; register designs for distinctive appearances; ensure trademark protection for brand. Product development integration: IP review at each development stage; invention disclosure process captures all innovations; design review identifies registrable appearances; coordinate with marketing for brand protection. Maintenance decisions: annual review of design and patent portfolios; consider protection scope vs maintenance cost; coordinate renewal decisions across IP types. Enforcement coordination: designs can be enforced faster (no examination means quicker to grant); use design enforcement while patent pending; combined actions strengthen overall position. Document integrated strategy for investor presentations and M&A due diligence.', '["Conduct IP audit across all protection types", "Identify layered protection opportunities", "Create integrated IP filing timeline", "Develop portfolio maintenance framework"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Integrated IP Audit Template", "Layered Protection Planner", "Multi-IP Filing Timeline", "Portfolio Review Framework"], "tools": ["IP Portfolio Dashboard", "Protection Gap Analyzer", "Maintenance Decision Tool", "IP Strategy Presentation Generator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 5, NOW(), NOW());
    INSERT INTO "Module" (id, "productId", title, description, "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
    INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, "moduleId", day, title, "briefContent", "actionItems", resources, "estimatedTime", "xpReward", "orderIndex", "createdAt", "updatedAt") VALUES
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_12_id, 56, 'IP Strategy for Early-Stage Startups', 'Early-stage startups (pre-seed to seed) need IP strategy despite resource constraints. Priority actions: (1) Founder IP assignment - ensure all founder contributions are assigned to company; use proper IP assignment agreements; address background IP brought in by founders. (2) Provisional patent filings - Rs 320 for DPIIT-registered startups; establishes early priority date; provides 12 months to assess commercial viability. (3) Confidentiality foundation - NDA template for all external discussions; employee confidentiality agreements from day one; visitor and contractor agreements. (4) Trade secret identification - document what information is confidential; implement basic security measures. Budget allocation: early-stage startups should allocate Rs 50,000-2 lakhs annually for IP protection; prioritize provisionals and NDAs; defer complete applications until commercial proof. IP considerations for incubators/accelerators: understand IP terms in program agreements; many programs do not take IP rights but review terms carefully; use program resources for IP guidance. Investor expectations: even early-stage investors expect founder IP assignment; some expect filed provisionals; demonstrate awareness of IP importance. Common mistakes: not assigning IP to company, discussing innovation without NDA, missing provisional deadline to complete, and treating IP as afterthought. Government support: DPIIT Startup India program facilitators provide free assistance; IPR facilitation centers offer guidance; state schemes may provide IP subsidies.', '["Complete founder IP assignment to company", "File provisional applications for core innovations", "Implement NDA and confidentiality framework", "Identify and document trade secrets"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["Founder IP Assignment Agreement", "Provisional Application Template", "Startup NDA Template", "Trade Secret Registry"], "tools": ["IP Assignment Checklist", "Provisional Filing Guide", "Startup India IP Resources", "State IP Scheme Finder"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 1, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_12_id, 57, 'IP for Fundraising and Due Diligence', 'Investors evaluate IP as part of due diligence; preparation strengthens position. Investor IP concerns: ownership (is IP properly assigned to company?); protection (are key innovations protected?); freedom to operate (are there blocking patents?); team (does team have IP expertise?); and value (is IP commercially relevant?). Due diligence preparation: IP assignment chain documented and complete; patent and design registration status updated; trade secret protection measures documented; FTO analysis for core products; IP-related litigation or disputes disclosed. Data room IP section: incorporation documents showing IP ownership; IP assignment agreements (founders, employees, contractors); patent applications and registrations (status, claims, office actions); license agreements (inbound and outbound); IP-related contracts (NDAs, development agreements); FTO opinions if available; and IP budget and filing plan. Investor presentation: IP slides showing portfolio size and coverage; key patents with claim summary; protection strategy aligned with business; competitive landscape and position. Valuation support: professional IP valuation helps justify higher valuation; demonstrate IP contribution to competitive moat; show alignment between IP and revenue. Common issues that delay/kill deals: missing founder assignments (especially pre-company work); IP still with previous employer; undisclosed license encumbrances; obvious FTO issues; and weak or no protection for core innovation. Address potential issues proactively before fundraising - retroactive fixes are difficult and raise concerns.', '["Audit IP ownership chain and fix gaps", "Prepare IP due diligence data room", "Conduct FTO assessment for core products", "Create investor-ready IP presentation"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["IP Due Diligence Checklist", "Data Room Structure Template", "FTO Summary Format", "IP Investor Deck Template"], "tools": ["Ownership Chain Validator", "Data Room Platform Guide", "Due Diligence Question Database", "Valuation Summary Generator"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 2, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_12_id, 58, 'Scaling IP Operations', 'Growing startups (Series A and beyond) need structured IP operations. Building IP function: assign IP responsibility (may be part-time initially); engage external IP counsel relationship; create invention capture process; establish IP decision-making governance. Invention harvesting: regular sessions with R&D teams to identify patentable innovations; invention disclosure form completion for each identified innovation; evaluation committee to prioritize filings; tracking system from disclosure to decision. IP metrics: filings per quarter/year; prosecution success rate; time from disclosure to filing; portfolio alignment with product roadmap; international coverage; competitive position. Scaling challenges: maintaining quality as filing volume increases; managing multiple external counsel relationships; coordinating international portfolio; balancing budget with opportunity. Process documentation: IP policy manual; invention disclosure procedures; filing decision criteria; patent prosecution guidelines; licensing authority matrix. Technology solutions: IP management software for portfolio tracking; deadline management systems; document management with security; collaboration tools for external counsel. Budget scaling: Series A companies typically allocate Rs 10-30 lakhs annually for IP; Series B and beyond may allocate Rs 30-100+ lakhs; budget should scale with product complexity and market expansion. Build relationships with patent agents who understand your technology - continuity improves drafting quality and prosecution efficiency.', '["Assign IP responsibility and create governance structure", "Implement invention harvesting process", "Establish IP metrics and tracking", "Select IP management technology"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["IP Policy Manual Template", "Invention Harvesting Protocol", "IP Metrics Dashboard", "Budget Planning Framework"], "tools": ["IP Management Software Comparison", "Invention Tracking System", "External Counsel Management Tool", "Budget Allocation Calculator"]}'::jsonb, 75, 50, 3, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_12_id, 59, 'IP in M&A and Exit', 'IP is central to startup M&A transactions as buyer or target. Seller considerations: IP due diligence preparation (ownership, protection, FTO, litigation); IP valuation for transaction pricing; IP representations and warranties (scope and limitations); indemnification for IP issues; employee IP retention (key inventors may need to stay); and IP-related earn-outs. Buyer considerations: thorough IP due diligence (ownership chain, prosecution status, validity risks); FTO for combined product portfolio; integration planning (align prosecution strategy, rationalize portfolio); employee retention (IP creators, prosecution knowledge); and hidden liabilities (undisclosed licenses, disputes). Key transaction documents: asset purchase agreement or stock purchase agreement with IP schedules; IP assignment documents for specific transfer; license agreements if seller retains any rights; employee agreements for key IP personnel. Indian law aspects: patent assignment must be registered with IPO (Form 16); design assignment registered with Design Office; trademark assignment with Trademark Registry; compulsory license rights (Sections 84-92) transfer with patent. Due diligence findings impact: clear ownership and strong protection commands premium; IP issues may reduce valuation or require escrow; material issues may be deal-breakers. Acqui-hire considerations: IP often secondary to team; ensure IP assignment from acquired entity; protect against inadvertent acquisition of problem IP. Post-transaction: complete all registrations; integrate IP management systems; communicate with continuing external counsel; update all IP-related agreements.', '["Prepare comprehensive IP due diligence package", "Value IP portfolio for transaction support", "Review standard IP representations and warranties", "Plan IP integration/transition"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["IP Due Diligence Disclosure Checklist", "IP Valuation Summary", "Representations and Warranties Guide", "IP Integration Plan Template"], "tools": ["M&A IP Checklist", "Transaction Document Library", "Registration Requirement Tracker", "Integration Planning Tool"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 4, NOW(), NOW()),
    (gen_random_uuid()::text, v_mod_12_id, 60, 'Building Long-Term IP Culture', 'Sustainable IP advantage requires embedding IP awareness throughout the organization. IP culture elements: leadership commitment (executives champion IP importance); broad awareness (all employees understand IP basics); systematic capture (innovations identified and evaluated); recognition (inventors acknowledged and rewarded); and continuous learning (regular IP training and updates). Training programs: basic IP awareness for all employees (what IP is, why it matters, company policies); detailed training for R&D (invention recognition, disclosure process, patentability basics); specialized training for technical leads (prior art searching, claim analysis, prosecution participation). Inventor recognition: inventor awards (certificates, monetary bonuses for filed/granted patents); public recognition (company announcements, patent wall); career consideration (IP contributions in performance reviews). Metrics and incentives: track invention disclosures per team; measure time from innovation to protection decision; reward high-quality disclosures; recognize prosecution participation. External ecosystem: patent agent relationships for quality and continuity; industry IP groups participation; academic collaborations with IP considerations; standard-setting organization involvement if relevant. Continuous improvement: annual IP strategy review; quarterly portfolio assessment; regular process refinement; benchmarking against industry peers. Long-term view: IP portfolio value compounds over time; consistent filing builds defensible position; culture ensures opportunities are not missed. The goal is making IP protection a natural part of innovation process, not a compliance afterthought. Companies with strong IP culture consistently outperform in competitive positioning, fundraising, and exit outcomes.', '["Develop IP training program for organization", "Establish inventor recognition system", "Create IP metrics and incentive alignment", "Build continuous improvement process"]'::jsonb, '{"templates": ["IP Training Curriculum", "Inventor Recognition Program Guide", "IP Metrics Dashboard", "Annual IP Review Template"], "tools": ["Training Module Creator", "Recognition Tracking System", "Benchmarking Tool", "Culture Assessment Survey"]}'::jsonb, 90, 60, 5, NOW(), NOW());
